<br>
I'd start my day by buffing fully first, then walking into the Courtyard invised.  Standing in a spot near the door (due to the fact that pathing caused the first garg to path near the fountain before coming towards you) i'd mez the garg.  Next i'd put my pet up and buff him with the appropriate AC buff, haste, resist magic and rampage/berserker spirit (level dependent).  After my pet was fully buffed i'd tash the garg (due to Uber high MR in SS), Slow with Shiftless deeds to preserver rune shield (Rampage/berserker spirit) on pet as long as possible, then DOT the garg.  After mez broke from the DOT i'd root the garg in place to avoid him coming after me and give pet time to gain agro.  From there i'd back up a safe distance to sit and med while my pet proceeded to slaughter the garg.  About the time it takes to med back the mana from the cast you can recast runeshield on your pet and sit again to continue medding.  Most important is to have root ready to go to make sure the garg doesn't get to the gate cause if he does it's a quick trip to CS for you.<br>
<br>
After this I would systematically pull my way around the room making sure to pull the melee classes first because if you pulled a caster first and it decided to cast instead of coming directly for you then guess where you're headed next...CS again.  Once the melee is safely out of the way you can tash or slow (I prefer the attempt to slow first because it saves the initial rounds of combat on your pet's runeshield here.  Then move close to the spot where the casting MOB is to gain agro for a sec til you get root off.  Then back away again, let pet gain agro, sit and med.  This strategy worked great for me and eventually forced me to drag twinks over to SS to loot guardian and sentry armor as I eventually got tired of watching BP's and such drop with no one there to loot.<br>
<br>
Soloing as a chanter has many viable ways of becoming a reality, though personally I prefer grouping to keep my more important skills up to par.  I have also solo'd Sentient suits with this method as well as wyverns in CS so don't knock what a chanter can do.  You're only limited by your imagination. <p></HEAD>
